{{infobox Museum |name= Anuradhapura Archaeological Museum |image=Vatadage-thuparama.jpg |caption =Model of Vatagage of the Thuparama in Anuradhapura |coordinates = |established= |founder = |location= [[Anuradhapura]], [[Sri Lanka]] |director= |visitors = |type = Archaeological |website= http://www.archaeology.gov.lk }}
'''Anuradhapura Archaeological Museum''' (Also known as '''Puravidu Bhavana''') is one of the archaeological museums of [[Sri Lanka]].<ref name="archaeo">{{cite web | url=http://www.archaeology.gov.lk/web/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=78&Itemid=86&lang=en | title=Anuradhapura Museum (National) | publisher=archaeology.gov.lk | accessdate=3 July 2015}}</ref> It is situated in the old [[kachcheri]] building, between the [[Lovamahapaya|Brazon palace]] and [[Ruwanwelisaya]]. The museum was established in 1947 under the prime effort of Dr. [[Senarath Paranavithana]].<ref name="tour"></ref> Anuradhapura Archaeological Museum is one of the oldest museum in the Cultural Triangle area<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.mysrilanka.com/travel/history/cul_trangle.htm| title=MUSEUMS IN THE CULTURAL TRIANGLE | publisher=mysrilanka.com| accessdate=3 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ceylonbestholiday4u.lk/1.html |title=Anuradhapura Archaeological Museum |publisher=ceylonbestholiday4u.lk |accessdate=3 July 2015 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130529005425/http://ceylonbestholiday4u.lk/1.html |archivedate=29 May 2013 }}</ref> and it has been proposed to name as the National Museum of the [[Department of Archaeology (Sri Lanka)|Department of Archaeology of Sri Lanka]].<ref name="archaeo"></ref>
The museum is used to exhibit antiquities found from various regions of Sri Lanka. Such as Buddha statues, inscriptions, drawings, puppets, coins, jewelleries, Beads and other miscellaneous things.<ref name="tour">{{cite web | url=http://tour.lk/sri_lanka/anuradhapura/archaeological_museum.php| title=Archaeological Museum | publisher=tour.lk| accessdate=3 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2003/09/14/fea11.html |title=Anuradhapura Archaeological Museum :Reflecting the rich heritage of the Rajarata | publisher=sundayobserver.lk| accessdate=3 July 2015}}</ref> Among these antiquities there is a model of the [[Thuparamaya]] Vatadage and a relic chamber found at [[Mihintale]] Kantaka Chetiya Dagoba.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.mysrilankaholidays.com/anuradhapura.html| title=The Sacred City of Anuradhapura, Sri Lanka | publisher=mysrilankaholidays.com| accessdate=3 July 2015}}</ref>
==Opening hours== The museum is open from 9.00 AM to 5.00 PM. It is closed on Tuesday and every public Holidays.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.srisalike.com/Museum/Anuradhapura/Anuradhapura%20Archaeological%20Museum.aspx| title=Anuradhapura Archaeological Museum | publisher=srisalike.com| accessdate=3 July 2015}}</ref>
