{{Infobox person | name = Ivan Tomko Mrnavić | image = Osmanchica.jpg | alt = | caption = Cover of the 1631 book ''Osmanchica'' authored by Mrnavić | birth_name = | birth_date = 1579 | birth_place = [[Šibenik|Sebenico (Šibenik)]], [[Republic of Venice]] | death_date = 1637 | death_place = Republic of Venice | nationality = Venetian | other_names = Ioannes Tomcvs Marnauitius | occupation = [[Catholic bishop]] and author of historical works | known_for = }}
'''Ivan Tomko Mrnavić''' ({{lang-la|Ioannes Tomcvs Marnauitius}}) (1579–1637) was a [[Republic of Venice|Venetian]] [[Catholic bishop]] and author of historical works.<ref name=Fine-421>{{Cite book |last=Fine |first=John V. A. |title=When Ethnicity Did Not Matter in the Balkans: A Study of Identity in Pre-Nationalist Croatia, Dalmatia, and Slavonia in the Medieval and Early-Modern Periods|url=https://books.google.com/books?ei=myayT9aRA4_zsgbOtIGTBA |location=Ann Arbor |publisher=University of Michigan Press |year=2006 |page=421}}</ref> He was the author of several forgeries, with the most famous being that of the "Life of [[Justinian]]".<ref name=Fine-421/> He also wrote a book on the Life of [[Saint Sava]].
== Views ==
Mrnavić believed that the [[Illyrians]] were Slavs.<ref name=Fine-421/> He claimed that [[Skanderbeg]], the national hero of [[Albania]], was of Slav origin, which prompted [[Frang Bardhi]] to write a biography on Skanderbeg published in Venice in 1636<ref>Georgius Castriotus Epirensis, vulgo Scanderbegh. Per Franciscum Blancum, De Alumnis Collegij de Propaganda Fide Episcopum Sappatensem etc. Venetiis, Typis Marci Ginammi, MDCXXXVI (1636).</ref> as a polemic against him, defending the Albanian identity of Skanderbeg.<ref name="Demiraj2007">{{cite book|last=Bartl|first=Peter|editor=Bardhyl Demiraj|title=Pjetër Bogdani und die Anfänge des alb. Buchdrucks|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qPtcT1oMeHAC&pg=PA273|accessdate=26 September 2012|series=Nach Vier hundert fünfzig Jahren|year=2007|publisher=Otto Harrassowitz Verlag|language=German|isbn=9783447054683|page=273}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Elsie|first=Robert|title=1959 Arshi Pipa: Communism and Albanian Writers|url=http://www.albanianhistory.net/texts20_3/AH1959.html|work=www.albanianhistory.net|accessdate=10 January 2012|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.albanianhistory.net%2Ftexts20_3%2FAH1959.html&date=2012-01-10|archivedate=10 January 2012|quote=He also raised his voice to defend the Albanian identity of Scanderbeg against a Slavic Catholic priest who claimed that our national hero was a Slav.}}</ref>
== Bibliography == His works written in Latin include: * ''Vita beati Augustini'' ([[Augustin Kažotić]]) * ''Vita Berislavi'' ([[Petar Berislavić]]) 1620 * ''Vita s. Sabbae'' ([[Saint Sava]]), Rome, 1630–31
His works written in "Illyrian" language include: * ''Život Margarite blažene divice, kćeri Bele, kralja ugarskoga i hrvatskoga'', 1613, translated from Italian * ''Žalosnoskazje Krispa Cezara'', 1614 - translated from Latin, tragedy of Bernarda Stefoni * ''Život Magdalene od knezov Žirova'', Rome 1626, Biblical-religious epic, translated to Italian, celebrating union of asceticism and anti-Turkish sentiment * ''Potuženje pokornika'', songs on death of Jesus, half of the poem is translated from song written on Latin by Sannazar * ''Osmanšćica'', drama written in 1631
