{{Infobox person | honorific_prefix = | name = Nora England | honorific_suffix = | birth_date = November 8, 1946 | birth_place = | nationality = American | ethnicity = <!-- Ethnicity should be supported with a citation from a reliable source --> | education = Ph.D. from the University of Florida | alma_mater = | occupation = American linguist, Mayanist, Dallas TACA Centennial Professor at the University of Texas at Austin | years_active = | employer = | organization = | known_for = She is founding director of the Center for Indigenous Languages of Latin America (CILLA). | notable_works = | style = | spouse = | awards = | website = | box_width = }}
'''Nora Clearman England''' (born November 8, 1946) is an [[United States|American]] [[linguist]], [[Mayanist]], and Dallas TACA Centennial Professor at [[University of Texas at Austin]].<ref>http://www.utexas.edu/cola/depts/linguistics/faculty/nce1946</ref>
She graduated from the [[University of Florida]] with a Ph.D. She taught at the [[University of Iowa]]. She led a workshop, and field visit to [[Iximche]], attended by [[Linda Schele]] and Nicholai Grube.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=QRxr0uuxw3kC&pg=PA311&dq=Nora+England&lr=&cd=16#v=onepage&q=Nora%20England&f=false ''The Code of Kings: The Language of Seven Sacred Maya Temples and Tombs'']</ref> She is founding director of the Center for Indigenous Languages of Latin America (CILLA).<ref>http://journals.dartmouth.edu/cgi-bin/WebObjects/Journals.woa/2/xmlpage/1/article/301?htmlOnce=yes</ref>
==Awards== * 1993 [[MacArthur Fellows Program]]
