[[File:Roman Empire - Mauretania Caesariensis (125 AD).svg|thumb|right|Mauretania Caesariensis (125 AD)]]
'''Turris in Mauretania''' is an ancient settlement of [[Roman North Africa]]  in the [[Roman province]] of [[Mauretania Caesariensis]].<ref>[http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/diocese/d3t57.html Turris in Mauretania], at catholic-hierarchy.org.</ref> The location is unknown but believed to be in [[Algeria]]. The city was believed to be the site of an ancient [[bishopric]]<ref>[http://www.gcatholic.org/dioceses/former/t1832.htm  Titular Episcopal See of Turris in Mauretania] at GCatholic.org.</ref> but no bishops of antiquity are known to us. The suffix "in Mauretania" is to differentiate the town from cities that existed in Spain and adjoining provinces of Roman North Africa.

The [[diocese]] remains today a [[titular see]] of the [[Roman Catholic Church]] in the [[ecclesiastical province]] of [[Carthage]].<ref>[http://www.gcatholic.org/dioceses/former/t1833.htm Titular Episcopal See of Turris in Proconsulari] at GCatholic.org.</ref> and is currently vacant.

